{
  "text": "All studies on the NYU-ADRC intervention displayed effective results. Depression was significantly reduced for family caregivers at four, eight and 12 months follow-up [CITATION_1] . This treatment effect for the same caregiver sample was sustained over three and five years [CITATION_2] . Furthermore, a modified NYU-ADRC intervention on a different caregiver sample showed that depression significantly improved across two years [CITATION_3] . Social support was also found to be improved by the NYU-ADRC intervention within a year [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and over five years (Drentea et al.) . This intervention was also effective for improving caregiver health at four months, two years and three years [CITATION_6] . However, one study on the NYU-ADRC intervention found non-significant positive effects on caregiver burden at one year (Roth et al.) . The two studies that examined the REACH II intervention showed positive results for depression [CITATION_7] and health [CITATION_8] .",
  "correct_citation": {
